<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1436,1503,2032]" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">
<bibRefCitation box="[151,478,1503,1528]" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" refId="ref14612" refString="Chemsak, J. A. &amp; Linsley, E. G. (1963) The genera of hesperophanine Cerambycidae presently known from Mexico, with descriptions of several new species. Journal of the Kansas Entomological Society, 36 (4), 207 - 230." type="journal article">Chemsak and Linsley (1963)</bibRefCitation>
described 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chemsak and Linsley" authorityYear="1963" box="[602,789,1503,1528]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Haplidus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nitidus">
<emphasis box="[602,789,1503,1528]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">Haplidus nitidus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chemsak and Linsley" authorityYear="1963" box="[845,1030,1503,1528]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Haplidus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mandibularis">
<emphasis box="[845,1030,1503,1528]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">H. mandibularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the same work, and both species from 
<collectingRegion box="[212,300,1539,1564]" country="Mexico" name="Mexico" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">
<collectingCountry box="[212,300,1539,1564]" name="Mexico" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">Mexico</collectingCountry>
</collectingRegion>
, respectively: 
<collectingRegion box="[460,553,1539,1564]" country="Mexico" name="Morelos" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">Morelos</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[606,686,1539,1564]" country="Mexico" name="Puebla" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">Puebla</collectingRegion>
. Still according to them, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chemsak and Linsley" authorityYear="1963" box="[963,1145,1539,1564]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Haplidus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mandibularis">
<emphasis box="[963,1145,1539,1564]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">H. mandibularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chemsak and Linsley" authorityYear="1963" box="[1292,1401,1539,1564]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Haplidus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nitidus">
<emphasis box="[1292,1401,1539,1564]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">H. nitidus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the prominent, bifid mandibles, narrower pronotum, and shorter antennal scape. However, the mandibles in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chemsak and Linsley" authorityYear="1963" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Haplidus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mandibularis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">H. mandibularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are very similar, although distinct longer in male, and the scape is also very similar in shape and length in both species. The difference in the proportions between scape and antennomere III reported in these species, is a common sexual dimorphism (scape longer than third segment [
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chemsak and Linsley" authorityYear="1963" box="[998,1108,1683,1708]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Haplidus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nitidus">
<emphasis box="[998,1108,1683,1708]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">H. nitidus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
]; scape subequal in length to third segment [
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chemsak and Linsley" authorityYear="1963" box="[320,504,1719,1744]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Haplidus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mandibularis">
<emphasis box="[320,504,1719,1744]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">H. mandibularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
]). The same regarding the prothoracic shape.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="202" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1436,1503,2032]" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">
Based in the original descriptions, examination of photographs of the 
<typeStatus box="[995,1104,1755,1780]" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">holotypes</typeStatus>
of both species, and detailed exam of a male, we concluded that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chemsak and Linsley" authorityYear="1963" box="[557,742,1791,1816]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Haplidus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mandibularis">
<emphasis box="[557,742,1791,1816]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">H. mandibularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the male of 
<emphasis box="[915,1034,1791,1816]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chemsak and Linsley" authorityYear="1963" box="[915,1031,1791,1816]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Haplidus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nitidus">H. nitidus</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Santos-Silva &amp; Botero &amp; Tirant" authorityYear="2018" box="[1042,1266,1791,1816]" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" rank="subSpecies" subSpecies="mandibularis">
As 
<emphasis box="[1082,1266,1791,1816]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">H. mandibularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chemsak and Linsley" authorityYear="1963" box="[1324,1435,1791,1816]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Haplidus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nitidus">
<emphasis box="[1324,1435,1791,1816]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">H. nitidus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were described in the same work (
<bibRefCitation box="[538,849,1827,1852]" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" refId="ref14612" refString="Chemsak, J. A. &amp; Linsley, E. G. (1963) The genera of hesperophanine Cerambycidae presently known from Mexico, with descriptions of several new species. Journal of the Kansas Entomological Society, 36 (4), 207 - 230." type="journal article">Chemsak and Linsley 1963</bibRefCitation>
) and the Principle of Priority does not apply (
<bibRefCitation pageId="13" pageNumber="202" refId="ref15034" refString="ICZN [International Commission on Zoological Nomenclature] (1999) International Code of Zoological Nomenclature, Fourth edition. International Trust of Zoological Nomenclature, London, xxx + 306 pp." type="book">
<collectionCode box="[1369,1436,1828,1852]" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">ICZN</collectionCode>
1999: Article 24.2.2
</bibRefCitation>
), we chose 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chemsak and Linsley" authorityYear="1963" box="[507,765,1863,1888]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Haplidus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mandibularis">
<emphasis box="[507,765,1863,1888]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">Haplidus mandibularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as the valid name because is in the males that the mandibles are long and falciform, the more conspicuous characteristic of the genus. After the original descriptions, these species were only mentioned in checklists and catalogues.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
